==English==

===Etymology===
From French '''[[unité]]''', from Latin '''[[unitas]]''', from adjective '''[[unus]]''', ''one'', + noun of state suffix '''[[-itas]]'''

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/ˈjunɪti/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|unities|-}}

# {{uncountable}} [[oneness]]; state of being one or undivided; united in mind or purpose
# {{cattag|drama}} {{countable}} any of the three classical rules of drama (unity of action, unity of place, and unity of time)
# {{cattag|mathematics}} {{countable}} any element of a set or field that behaves with respect to a given function like the number 1 does with respect to multiplication

====Related terms====
*[[unique]]
*[[unus]]

